items.description: The Admissions Office is located in the Kim S. Phipps Admissions and Welcome Center. The Admissions team is available to help guide prospective students through the process of visiting campus, learning more about Messiah, applying, obtaining scholarships and answering questions students may have about a future at Messiah.

items.description:
Messiah University has one visitor parking lot located between the Kim Phipps Welcome Center and Old Main.

Download a more detailed parking map

The Agapé Center for Service Learning develops, administers resources and coordinates programs of service-learning, community service and missions. Students, faculty and staff work with community-based partners in various settings to address community needs, provide holistic learning opportunities for students and encourage students toward an ethic of discipleship, service and civic engagement.

The Office of Alumni and Parent Relations is located in the Kim S. Phipps Admissions and Welcome Center. This office strives to serve our 27,000+ living alumni and nearly 6,000 parents through informative communications, memorable events and strategic programs that create meaningful engagement.
items.parent_building_name: Kim S. Phipps Admissions and Welcome Center

items.description: The Alumni Plaza is a community space dedicated by those who call Messiah University their alma mater. Each year, alumni reunion classes engage in a friendly competition to encourage classmates to give a financial gift to the University in honor of their class. This plaza honors the class with the highest participation of giving back. We are grateful for those who have gone before and choose to continue the legacy of Messiah University.
This artificial, lighted turf field is home to the Messiah University women’s field hockey team. It is made of the newest and best materials in artificial turf.

items.entry_title: Archives (Messiah University, BIC and Ernest L. Boyer Center)
items.description:
On the lower level of Murray Library are the archives for Messiah University, the Brethren in Christ Church and The Ernest L. Boyer Center. 
 
The Archives of Messiah University contains the official records of the University's governing boards, administrative and educational departments, and student organizations.
 
The Ernest L. Boyer Archives at Messiah University contains manuscripts, audio and visual materials, correspondence, records of appointments, and other artifacts documenting the life and work of this American educational pioneer.
 
The Archives of the Brethren in Christ Church is the official home for records generated by boards, agencies, and institutions of the denomination.
An ATM is located outside of the Falcon, located on the ground floor of Eisenhower Campus Center.
An ATM is located on the lower level of Larsen Student Union.

The Auginbaugh Art Gallery is located on the ground floor of Climenhaga Building. It features new exhibitions on a monthly basis that are designed to be of interest to the campus and community. The artwork displayed is created by nationally recognized artists, Messiah’s art faculty and our students.

Messiah's baseball field is often considered one of the best playing surfaces in the conference--and the region. Natural amphitheater seating on the hillside behind the backstop, combined with the playing surface below, makes for a great view for fans and spectators.

Bittner Residence is a co-ed, first-year residence hall for 180 students. Bittner has two male floors and two female floors. Each room in Bittner is carpeted, air conditioned, and has access to the campus satellite TV and connections to the residential computer network. The lower level houses a study room and conference room.
The Bowmansdale Building is located at the intersection of Lisburn and Bumble Bee Hollow Roads and is home to University Press, which provides printing services to the campus community.
Boyer Hall is the largest academic building on Messiah's campus and houses education and social sciences departments, the School of the Humanities, and Parmer Cinema, a full-scale movie theater.
The Brethren In Christ offices are located on the grounds of the Grantham Brethren in Christ Church at 431 Grantham Road, Mechanicsburg.
Located in Eisenhower Campus Center, Brubaker Auditorium comfortably seats over 1,800 spectators.
Café Diem is located directly inside Murray Library and features coffee, specialty drinks and pastries.

items.entry_title: Calvin and Janet High Center for Worship and Performing Arts
items.description: The High Center for Worship and Performing Arts is a 92,000-square-foot facility with classroom, office and rehearsal space for the School of the Arts. The centerpiece of the building is Parmer Hall, a performance hall complete with a choir loft and pipe organ. Also within the Center is the High Foundation Recital Hall.

items.entry_title: Calvin and Janet High Center for Worship and Performing Arts
items.description: The Calvin and Janet High Center for Worship and Performing Arts is a 92,000-square-foot facility with classroom, office and rehearsal space for the School of the Arts. The centerpiece of the building is Parmer Hall, a performance hall complete with a choir loft and pipe organ. Also within the Center is the High Foundation Recital Hall.

Campus Ministries is located on the first floor of Hostetter Chapel. Messiah University Ministries wants to help students grow in their faith, and they offer plenty of opportunities for students to explore various facets of their faith and learn more about who God is. This is done through student worship opportunities, chapel, and more.
The Campus Store, located on the ground floor of Eisenhower Campus Center, sells books; apparel and accessories; gifts and collectibles; school and office supplies; technology; and more.

The Career and Professional Development Center (CPDC) is located on the ground floor of Eisenhower Campus Center. The CPDC provides students tools for career exploration, planning and decision making through internship opportunities, career coaching, major selection and more.

The combined cooling, heat and power plant (CCHP), located behind Sollenberger Sports Center, is an efficient and environmentally friendly energy source that provides campus with year-round electric power.

Climenhaga Building is home to office, classroom, rehearsal and performance spaces. Miller Theater, Poorman Black Box Theater, Pollock Dance Studio and the Aughinbaugh Art Gallery are all located in Climenhaga Building.
The Climenhaga Homestead includes guest suites and a full-service conference room and meeting facility.

There are multiple commuter student parking lots located on the Messiah University campus. Commuter students must have a parking permit to park in these areas on campus.
Download a more detailed parking map

Conference and Event Services is located on the first floor of Eisenhower Campus Center. This department consists of conference services (event planning, room reservations), sound and lighting, university reception and the ticket office.

The Covered Bridge is a familiar landmark on the Messiah campus, located above the Yellow Breeches Creek. Officially named "The Bowmansdale Bridge," the bridge connects the rest of campus to Starry Athletic Fields.

Adjacent to Anderson Field are six match-quality tennis courts (hard) that are home to the Falcons' men's and women's tennis teams. In addition, there are four recreational courts adjacent to the Covered Bridge. Together they comprise the Criste Courts.
The Department of Safety Office is located at 432 Grantham Road, adjacent to the main entrance of the University and provides safety and security services for Messiah’s campus.

The Development Office is located on the third floor of Old Main. They are responsible for engaging alumni, parents and friends in financial support of the University so that our educational mission may flourish. Such support includes annual gifts for the Messiah Fund, gifts for various capital projects, endowment gifts for student scholarships, and longer-term gifts in the form of bequests or charitable trusts.

The Dining Services Office is located on the first floor of Eisenhower Campus Center. The dining team team has won awards in local and national culinary competitions and is consistently recognized for excellence in food safety. They work to provide delicious food at all dining facilities and catered events.

The Dispatch Office is located on the ground floor of Eisenhower Campus Center. Working under the Department of Safety, dispatch has direct contact with local emergency services agencies; handles lost and found items; distributes emergency battery jump packs for dead car batteries; and performs many other tasks to keep the campus community safe.

Eisenhower Campus Center contains Brubaker Auditorium; Campus Store; student mailboxes and U.S. Post Office services; Lottie Nelson Dining Hall; the Falcon; University Reception and Dispatch; Ticket Office; Career and Professional Development Center; Office of Sustainability; and Office of Alumni and Parent Relations as well as various other administrative offices for dining services, residence life, campus events and more.

Nineteen emergency phones are located in multiple locations around campus. These phones may be used to call for assistance in the case of an emergency. They may also be used in non-emergency situations like requesting an escort to your on-campus destination after dark.

There are multiple employee parking lots, outlined here by the red lines, located on the Messiah University campus. Only employees with a parking permit are allowed to park in these areas.

Download a more detailed parking map
The Engle Center houses counseling and health services for the Messiah University community. The center employs professional counselors, nurses and other health practitioners.

The Falcon Exchange is located on the first floor of Eisenhower Campus Center, next to Lottie Nelson Dining Hall. They issue campus ID cards; student vehicle registration; Falcon dining dollars and more.
The Falcon Fitness Center, a 14,374 square foot facility filled with state-of-the-art cardiovascular, strength and group exercise equipment, is home to all of your fitness needs.

The Falcon Hut is located just across from Starry Athletic Field. The Falcon Hut is open for home soccer, baseball and softball games, as well as some special events. The Hut serves soft pretzels, hot dogs, candy, cookies, fruit, coffee and soda.

The Financial Aid Office is located on the third floor of the Kim Phipps Welcome Center. They serve students, parents, Messiah University colleagues and the community by providing information and services to enable students to attain the funding necessary to realize their educational goals.
items.parent_building_name: Kim S. Phipps Admissions and Welcome Center

items.description: The famous campus fishbowl is a distinguishing feature of Grantham Residence. The fishbowl is a large, main lounge outfitted with televisions, comfortable furniture and a recreation area.
The Fredricksen Natatorium is located on the ground floor of Sollenberger Sports Center.

Frey Hall houses classrooms; a large lecture hall; art studios for sculpture, ceramics, graphic design, foundations and printmaking; computer labs; generous engineering lab and project workspace; physics labs; and faculty offices. Many business, engineering, computer science, mathematics and art courses are held in Frey Hall.

Fry residence houses 220 in its 52 one- and two-bedroom apartments. Each apartment has an individual kitchen and bathroom; laundry facilities are located in the building’s basement. Outdoor sand volleyball and basketball courts are nearby.

This renovated studio is used as dance classroom space, theatre and dance rehearsal space and small dance concert venue for student presentations. This studio is a 1,600 square-foot room with 1,144 square-feet covered by a raised Marley floor. Mirrors and bars line two walls, and masking curtains are used to create a small performance space. Included in this space are a small lighting grid and ETC 48 circuit dimmer rack, an ETC Smartfade lighting console with a small sound system and flat screen TV monitor, and live feed video camera for use in teaching or presentations.

Grantham Hall currently houses approximately 200 upper-class students. The third floor houses male students and the lower three floors house women. This residence connects the Hess and Miller residences of the North Complex. Grantham Hall features a recreation room, large main lounge, and television lofts. It is one of the newest residence halls built on campus. Each room is carpeted, air conditioned, and has access to the campus satellite TV and connections to the campus residential computer network.

Hess is a co-ed residence for approximately 135 upper class students. Hess is part of the North Complex along with Miller and Grantham Residence Halls. Each room is carpeted, air conditioned and has access to the campus satellite TV and campus residential network.
The High Center Galleries are located on the first and second floor of the High Center.
High Foundation Recital Hall is located on the ground floor of High Center. The Department of Music hosts small concerts and events in this space, as well as student recitals.
The Hitchcock Arena is located on the ground floor of Sollenberger Sports Center.

Hostetter Chapel houses Messiah's Campus Ministries department. The chapel also contains a beautiful sanctuary, which is used for a variety of campus concerts, gatherings and other events. In the basement of Hostetter is a state-of-art media and film production studio.

Human Resources and Compliance is located on the first floor of Old Main. Their focus is the attraction, retention and development of employees; administration of health and retirement benefits; and more.

Information Technology Services is located on various floors in Old Main. ITS and its various departments are responsible for all college servers; data storage; backup; authentication; network; wireless; voice communications; and implementation and support of many of Messiah University's data and operational systems.
The Information/Reception office is located on the ground floor of Eisenhower Campus Center.

Located in Larsen Student Union, the Intercultural Office at Messiah University houses three distinct but interconnected areas: International Student Programs, Multicultural Programs and Off-Campus Programs.

The Jordan Science Center houses state-of-the-art classrooms and laboratories for students in the natural and health sciences, along with faculty offices. Jordan also houses the Oakes Museum of Natural History.

Kelly residence houses 180 upper-class students in its one- and two bedroom all female and all male apartments on the north side of campus. Each apartment has an individual kitchen and bathroom; laundry facilities are located in the building’s basement. Kelly also has a computer lab, and it has an adjacent parking lot and a sand volleyball court nearby, a grill and picnic table.

items.entry_title: Kim S. Phipps Admissions and Welcome Center
items.description: The new Kim S. Phipps Admissions and Welcome Center is a centralized space for prospective students. In addition to the undergraduate Admissions Office, the Welcome Center will also house other offices that work collaboratively to recruit and retain students, including Financial Aid and Financial Services, the Registrar’s Office, and the Office of Alumni and Parent Relations.
Kline Hall of Science houses classrooms, science and nursing labs, faculty offices and computer labs.
This lighted synthetic turf field is the primary home of Messiah’s men’s and women’s lacrosse teams.

The Larsen Student Union is the hub for student life on campus. It includes dining and recreational space; a stage for concert and events; student programming offices; and houses The Pulse: Messiah University Media Hub which includes the yearbook, student newspaper and Messiah's student-run radio station (90.7 FM).
Lenhert Maintenance Building is home to offices for campus operations such grounds, mechanical and building services that keep the campus functioning.
The locker rooms are located in the basement of Eisenhower Campus Center.

Lottie Nelson Dining Hall, located on the first floor of Eisenhower Campus Center, is an all-you-care-to-eat facility that features a wide range of fresh foods and menu options during each meal period.
The main entrance of Messiah University is located on Grantham Road, adjacent to Grantham Brethren in Christ Church.

The Office of Marketing and Communications is located on the third floor of Old Main. They tell Messiah University’s story through a variety of different mediums, including the website, print brochures, newsletters, a quarterly magazine and social media.

The Martin Commons, adjacent to Lottie Nelson Dining Room on the first floor of Eisenhower Campus Center, offers 4,800 square feet of dining space, with a capacity of about 260 guests. With its contemporary design and natural light, the venue provides student and conference dining space throughout the year, but also private areas for campus catering and special events.
McBeth Advancement Center houses staff and services that support the work of the Messiah University Advancement Division.

Mellinger provides housing for about 180 upper-class students in its 41 one- and two-bedroom all male and all female apartments. Each apartment has an individual kitchen and bathroom; laundry facilities are located in the building’s basement. Mellinger also has adjacent parking, a computer lab, a grill and picnic table.

Miller residence is a traditional upper class co-ed residence for approximately 135 students. In Miller, each room is carpeted, air conditioned, and has access to the campus satellite TV and residential computer network.
Miller Theater serves as the primary performance space for Department of Theatre productions. This proscenium style house offers fixed seating for approximately 380 patrons.

Mountain View Residence Hall houses approximately 210 upper-class students. Mountain View has three female floors and two male floors. This residence connects Bittner and Sollenberger residences of the South Complex. Each room is carpeted, air conditioned, and also has access to the campus satellite TV and connections to the campus residential network.

The MUHP Harbor House is home to a group of 10 women in the Honors Program who are dedicated to fostering an environment of conversation, connection, camaraderie, and comfort. The house organizes monthly tea and coffee discussions on diverse topics, offers open-house study sessions every Monday, and hosts monthly recreational events for MUHP students.

Murray Library provides a wide variety of learning resources, housing more than 295,000 items in its collections, while also connecting patrons to electronic databases and websites. The library also has computer labs, digital editing labs, Café Diem coffee shop, and the Messiah University Archives.

Naugle is a first-year, co-ed dorm which is similar in design to Witmer. It houses approximately 275 students in an air-conditioned and carpeted traditional residence. Floors have kitchens and study rooms. Connections to the campus residential network are available in individual rooms and various common spaces.

Located in Murray Library, the Office of Academic Accessibility supports and accommodates students with a wide range of physical, psychological and learning disabilities, both in and out of the classroom. Housing accommodations are provided for many students with chronic health problems or physical limitations.
Old Main is the primary administrative building on campus. It houses key areas like President’s office, provost’s office, human resources, development, and marketing and communications.
Orchard Hill, located on Lisburn Road, is home to Messiah's president and her family. The many public spaces of Orchard Hill are used to host dinners and receptions for campus and community groups.
Parmer Cinema, located on the first floor of Boyer Hall, seats 125 and features state-of-the-art acoustics and projection.
Parmer Cinema, located on the first floor of Boyer Hall, seats 125 and features state-of-the-art acoustics and projection.

Parmer Hall, located in the Calvin and Janet High Center for Worship and Performing Arts, is an expanded performing arts venue with seating for 825, along with choir loft seating for 140-160. It is used for concerts, public lectures and special events.

Poorman Black Box Theater offers a venue for the exploration of the art of theatre in an intimate, up-to-date environment. This flexible space serves both as a classroom as well as a performance venue for plays, musicals, and other theatre productions.
The University has three irrigated 120' x 75' practice fields for use by various sports.
The President's office is located on the second floor of Old Main.
The Private Dining Room is located on the first floor of Eisenhower Campus Center.

The Provost's Office is located on the second floor of Old Main. This office oversees and provides leadership to all of the educational programming of the University, which includes both academic and co-curricular programming.
The Racquetball courts are located on the ground floor of Sollenberger Sports Center.

The Rafiki house is an on-campus, special interest house serving international students. It is dedicated to providing a place of support and fellowship for international, missionary and transcultural students and also serves as a hub for ISA/MuKappa student activities.

The Reconciliation House is part of the Peace and Conflict Studies (PACS) academic program; however, the house is open to students of all majors who are interested in issues of reconciliation and social justice. The Reconciliation House is specifically for men.
The Recreational Sports Fields are located along Grantham Road, directly across the railroad tracks.

The Registrar's Office is located on the first floor of the Kim Phipps Welcome center. They take responsibility for student academic records and maintain their files from the initial semester of registration through graduation.
items.parent_building_name: Kim S. Phipps Admissions and Welcome Center

items.description: The Restoration House is one of Messiah's special interest houses. The goal of students who apply to live in this house is to restore the image of Messiah students living off campus to one of an active and engaged part of the Messiah community.

Shoemaker Field is a lighted, full-size, top-quality, match-only grass field used by the men's and women's soccer programs. The facility has bleacher seating for several thousand spectators and significant standing room, along with seating for any of our visitors with disabilities.

Smith houses 150 upper-class students in its 36 one- and two-bedroom all female and all male apartments. Each apartment has an individual kitchen and bathroom; laundry facilities are located in the building’s basement. Smith also has an outdoor grill and picnic table.

Starry Field is the home of the Messiah University softball team. It features enclosed brick dugouts, electronic scoreboard, a press box, audio system, outdoor batting cages and a fully enclosed playing field.

Sollenberger Residence, or "Solly" as it is often called, houses approximately 180 upper-class students. The second and third floors of Solly house men and the first and basement floors house women. Each room is carpeted, air conditioned, and has access to the campus satellite TV and residential computer network.

The Sollenberger Sports Center provides Messiah University with exceptional recreational and intercollegiate athletic facilities. Completed in 1985 and currently undergoing renovations and additions, this complex houses racquetball courts, a large arena with four basketball courts, an indoor track and fitness center, a natatorium including an eight-lane swimming pool, classrooms, locker rooms, and wrestling and gymnastics areas. Eisenhower Campus Center, where most indoor intercollegiate contests are held, offers additional facilities.

The Sollenberger Sports Center provides Messiah University with exceptional recreational and intercollegiate athletic facilities. Completed in 1985 and currently undergoing renovations and additions, this complex houses racquetball courts, a large arena with four basketball courts, an indoor track and fitness center, a natatorium including an eight-lane swimming pool, classrooms, locker rooms, and wrestling and gymnastics areas. Eisenhower Campus Center, where most indoor intercollegiate contests are held, offers additional facilities.
Messiah University's south entrance is located at the intersection of University Avenue and Creekside Drive, adjacent to the beautiful Yellow Breeches Creek.

Beginning to the west of the covered bridge along Creekside Drive and ending in the parking lot behind Naugle Residence Hall, Messiah’s Stabler Fitness Trail winds along the Yellow Breeches and lends itself to both solitary and group outdoor activities.
Starry Athletic Field Complex consists of Anderson Field, Criste Courts, the Messiah University Baseball Complex, Shoemaker Field, Starry Field and a new lacrosse field.
The Student Activities Board (SAB) is a campus organization which provides the student body with a variety of events and activities, including dances, concerts, coffeehouses and films.

Located in Larsen Student Union, the Student Government Association (SGA) is a multi-tiered organization. In addition to its 70 clubs and organizations, SGA also has three main administrative branches: the Student Senate, the Peer Review Board and the Student Body President’s Cabinet.

There are multiple student parking lots located on the Messiah University campus. Students must have a parking permit to park in these areas on campus.

Download a more detailed parking map

Student Success and Engagement is located on the first floor of Eisenhower Campus Center. They work to develop the whole student through a co-curriculum that assesses the outcome of each student's learning and character development.

The Office of Sustainability is located on the ground floor of Eisenhower Campus Center, beside The Falcon. Messiah University integrates creation care throughout every part of the institution, touching operations, academics, co-curricular experiences and community partnerships.

The Ernest L. Boyer Center is located on the first floor of Boyer Hall. It contains manuscripts, audio and visual materials, correspondence, records of appointments, and other artifacts documenting the life and work of this American educational pioneer.

The Falcon is located on the ground floor of Eisenhower Campus Center beside The Campus Store. They serve breakfast sandwiches, paninis, soups, tossed salads, rice bowls, chicken tenders, grab n' go products and various daily features.

The Learning Center is located in Murray Library. It offers tutoring in a number of subjects, including but not limited to biology, chemistry, nursing, Spanish, French and German. Individual and group tutoring is offered to all Messiah students free of charge.
The Loft has an indoor climbing wall and a great room, a hospitable place for group meetings.

items.entry_title: The Oakes Museum of Natural History
items.category_name: The Oakes Museum of Natural History
items.description: The Oakes Museum of Natural History is located on the ground floor of Jordan Science Center. It is a unique museum experience for the family, classroom or group featuring over 40,000 specimens. The 10,000-square foot museum is home to a collection of Smithsonian quality African and North American mammals, birds, eggs, fish, seashells, minerals, insects and fossils.
The Pulse--Messiah University's media hub--is located on the ground floor of Larsen Student Union. It consists of Pulse FM, The Clarion yearbook and The Swinging Bridge magazine.

The Ticket Office is located on the ground floor of Eisenhower Campus Center. The staff seeks to provide courteous and efficient customer service at a central location for the students, staff, faculty and community clients to purchase tickets for Messiah University events.

The Ticket Office is located on the ground floor of Eisenhower Campus Center. The staff seeks to provide courteous and efficient customer service at a central location for the students, staff, faculty and community clients to purchase tickets for Messiah University events.

The Union Café, located on the ground floor of Larsen Student Union, serves a wide range of food including sandwiches, tossed salads, burgers, pizza, cheesesteaks, quesadillas, ice cream, smoothies, coffee and specialty drinks, and a variety of grab n' go items.

Messiah University Press produces and assists in the production of Messiah University-sponsored communications which inform, engage, and connect the broader Messiah community in support of the University's mission.

Messiah University has one visitor parking lot, outlined here by the purple lines, located between the Kim Phipps Welcome Center and Old Main.

Download a more detailed parking map

Witmer Residence houses approximately 300 students in an air-conditioned and carpeted traditional residence. The building has four floors that are usually split evenly between male and female students. Floor kitchens, study rooms, computer lab, and connections to the residential computer network and dance studio in the basement are some of the amenities.
The Wrestling Room is located on the ground floor of Sollenberger Sports Center.

The Writing Center is located on the first floor of the Murray Library. The Writing Center tutors work to improve students' writing proficiency in any area of study through individual sessions with trained peers.
